adjectives.description: outback (comparative more outback, superlative most outback)

entries.meaning: Characteristic of the most remote and desolate areas of Australia; very remote from urban areas.
examples: […] the Civil Service Association is not particularly happy with the decision of the Government in regard to rents and the way they will be levied on its members in the more outback country areas.

entries.meaning: To or towards the most remote and desolate areas of Australia.
examples: If we want this country to develop, we have to depend on men who are prepared to go outback and try to discover new shows.

entries.meaning: (Australia) The most remote and desolate areas of Australia; the desert and areas too arid for growing crops.
examples: Communication like this is making a big change in the lives of Australia′s “outback” people.

verbs.description: outback (third-person singular simple present outbacks, present participle outbacking, simple past and past participle outbacked)

entries.meaning: To travel or stay in the outback
